How do you get stronger without getting bigger? Here’s what Jordan Syatt @syattfitness who deadlifted 530 lbs at 130 lbs bodyweight had to say on a prior SquatU podcast episode.🏋🏼‍♂️
.
“Outside of nutrition, speed and power development are underutilized for improving maximal strength and is something we don’t talk about enough.” Focusing on not only improving how much force you can produce (lifting big weight), but your rate of force development (how fast you can move a weight), can help you lift more weight in the long run. Improving your RFD can allow you to improve overall strength without necessarily having to gain muscle mass as well. This means trying to move sub-maximal weight as FAST as possible!🔥
.
This clip is from episode 67 of the Squat University podcast. Also be sure to follow @syattfitness on IG. Jordan has a wealth of knowledge to share with everyone on all things fitness related.📲

Do your elbows bend too early during a clean or snatch? One effective way to fix this common fault is to slow the movement down and pause above the knee with focus on keeping your triceps flexed. This can help teach your body how to maintain straighter elbows through your extension phase of the lift. 
.
This is in fact something that I have experienced myself in my cleans in the past – you can see in this 145 kg clean my elbows lock into a slightly flexed position right off the floor and then straighten back out as I go into extension. With the tips from 2x Olympian @Olychad as my coach you can see big changes in my clean compared to before. 
.

If you need to improve shoulder external rotation, you'll likely look up someone cranking their shoulder backwards with a PVC pipe stretch like I'm showing at the start of this video. Now while there can be a time and place for this exercise in some situations, I rarely find this is an OPTIMAL choice for many. Too often this stretch is performed WAY TO AGGRESSIVELY and for the wrong person.❌ 
.
Most athletes do not lack shoulder external rotation because their JOINT needs to be stretched but because the larger muscles that attach to the shoulder and perform the movement of internal rotation are stiff/tight (lats and pecs specifically). This means doing some simple flexibility work with the pecs and lats can instantly improve external rotation. 
.
If you'd like to watch the rest of this video, including exercises to improve lat flexibility, check out the YouTube video "Back Squat Shoulder Mobility (Fix Your Rack Position)"📲

Here’s some behind the scenes rehab of a recent patient dealing with hip pain with squatting actions. This particular clip is of us working on the touchdown squat exercise. During the start of this exercise she had a small amount of pain, which was taken away with an RNT addition to the drill. 
.
This goes to show how her hip pain had a direct connection to the stability her hips need to make for more optimal movement. Is this a final fix? Not by itself - we also worked on banded joint mobilizations and other stability drills before this - BUT this is a key part of the full fix. Understanding how we can modify symptoms in real time, give access to new motion & allow for improved quality of movement is an essential part of the evaluation & rehabilitation program. Remember there is no one size fits all program for fixing any injury. It all comes down to a proper evaluation & individualizing our fixes based on what we find. 
.

When someone asks “Are deadlifts good for low back pain rehab?” the answer is usually yes…but WHEN they are implanted is always “it depends!”
.
Today I’m sharing 2 patients of mine who both had pain with deadlifts and both had MRI scans that showed bulging discs. However the movement evaluation I performed (with many tests I learned first from renowned back expert @backfitpro) showed they had different triggers for their pain. For this reason, both could not tolerate deadlifting from the ground at the start of their rehab. This is why a “one size fits all approach” to rehab for any injury does NOT work. While both got back to deadlifting - their path was different.
.
Shout out @mrsc_boehm & @krispy_kremez for being my patient models for the day.
.
If you’re dealing with low back pain and want to learn what your movement diagnosis is, check out my blog “How to screen your low back pain” on Squatuniversity.com & the different case study videos on my YouTube channel.

node.text:
I get it, I’ve been there. One of the biggest things that holds athletes back from taking necessary steps back in order to fix a technique issue or small injury is the fear that all the progress they’ve worked so hard for over the years will be lost. 
.
The thought of dropping weight and not pushing heavy brings out anxiety in a lot of people & if you really examine why it comes down to two things. 
.
First, many of us have our ego wrapped up in how much we are capable of lifting. Taking a step back and having others see us lift much lighter weights than normal is a shot to that ego. 
.
Second, we don’t trust the process. We want our results and weights now. We don’t realize that taking a small step back is not a forever loss of the progress you’ve worked so hard for but often a necessary step so you can take 3 more steps forward eventually.
.
If this is you, trust me I’ve been there too. Trust the process, drop your ego & good will come.

If you have a problem with your toes picking up during the pull of your clean or snatch lifts, try this lifting progression as demonstrated by 2x Olympian Chad Vaughn. 
.
You’re going to start barefoot so you can become more aware of your foot position. Perform a slow pull to the above knee position and pause for 2 seconds feeling for your big toes staying jammed down into the ground – THEN finish your lift. You can follow this with a regular tempo lift without a pause after with the focus on keeping your big toes jammed down during the pull. 
.
After a 1-3 sets barefoot, put your lifting shoes on and perform the same progression – seeing if you can maintain that same stable foot with the big toes down now that you have your shoes on. The idea is to slow the lift down and pause at the crucial position above the knee where the problem usually comes out  and become more aware of your balance. 
.
Shout out @samanthiccccc for sharing her first lift & @olychad for the collaboration in the fix!

node.text:
Progress is never linear. We all have good days and bad. One thing that I can’t preach enough is that we should all intend to move with amazing technique every single time we touch the barbell (no matter if it’s a warm up weight or your heaviest set of the day). Some days you'll feel great & everything seems to click. Others, it feels like no matter how hard you try - things just feel like 💩. However, you if you never give up the pursuit of perfecting technique - good things will happen in the end.🏋🏼‍♀️
.
It’s how you react when the bad days when they happen that matters. Learn from them, move on and crush your next training session.🥊

In order to keep your back position strong and  maintain stability on the descent you teach yourself how to “own” every aspect to the rep. Adding these in to your program will not only enhance your capacity but also your resiliency for future lifting.

node.text:
“Toe spring” describes the elevation of the toe box from the ground. If you closely examine many of your shoes (especially those designed for athletics) the front tip will be elevated a few degrees. Originally this feature was built into thick and inflexible shoes as a way to help “roll” the foot forward as you walk. Think about this as having the bottom of a rocking chair on your foot. 
.
So why is this a problem? 
.
Toe spring basically forces the toes of your foot “out of business.” Your foot was designed to have all of your toes completely flat on the ground when weightbearing. This allows the toes to grasp the ground and provide stability for the entire foot and therefore the rest of the body. Because 18 of the foot’s 19 tendons are attached to the toes, allowing them to remain flat essentially anchors your entire foot to the ground and enhances stability (one reason why toe spring on a weightlifting shoe makes absolutely zero functional sense). 
.
So if you currently wear a pair of shoes that has toe spring to the gym - you’d be better off going barefoot!

How do you get stronger without getting bigger? Here’s what Jordan Syatt @syattfitness who deadlifted 530 lbs at 130 lbs bodyweight had to say on a prior SquatU podcast episode.🏋🏼‍♂️
.
“Outside of nutrition, speed and power development are underutilized for improving maximal strength and is something we don’t talk about enough.” Focusing on not only improving how much force you can produce (lifting big weight), but your rate of force development (how fast you can move a weight), can help you lift more weight in the long run. Improving your RFD can allow you to improve overall strength without necessarily having to gain muscle mass as well. This means trying to move sub-maximal weight as FAST as possible!🔥
.
This clip is from episode 67 of the Squat University podcast. Also be sure to follow @syattfitness on IG. Jordan has a wealth of knowledge to share with everyone on all things fitness related.📲

Here’s the deal, deadlifting is actually NOT as dangerous as some have made it out to be. However let’s say you’re currently dealing with hip pain WHEN deadlifting like a hip impingement or labrum injury that brings out pain in the very bottom position of the lift. Now the last thing you want to do is to tell yourself its all in your head and continue pushing through it – things will only get worse. We also don’t want to COMPLETELY step away from lifting and go back to the PVC pipe. 
.
You see when you’re hurt your injured tissue currently has a capacity much lower than your ability to tolerate prior “normal” loading. If you completely deload your capacity will lower EVEN MORE. However, if we take the approach of training what we can while we fix what we can fix – it allows our body to slowly rebuild capacity at the most optimal rate. For example, if you couldn’t deadlift from the floor – an option for some may be a deadlift from the blocks. This will allow you to maintain strength in positions you can tolerate without pain during rehab as you slowly rebuild your prior lifts. 
.
Any injury fix starts with understanding what is triggering pain and then evaluating what problems are leading to the problem. This is often a mixture of movement problems (stability deficits, mobility restrictions, etc) and improper loading. Once uncovered with a proper evaluation we can craft a plan that allows you to get back to 100%! 
.
